ABAKALIKI – The Election Petitions Tribunal sitting in Ebonyi State, on Tuesday, granted leave to the Governorship candidate of the People’s Democratic Party (PDP), Mr Ifeanyi Chukwuma Odii and that of the All Progressives Grand Alliance (APGA) Professor Bernard Odoh to inspect documents used by the Independent National Electoral Commission (INEC) for the conduct of the March 18 governorship election in the State. This followed two separate Exparte Applications filed by Messrs Odii and Odoh, who came second and third respectively in the governorship election won by Francis Nwifuru of the All Progressives Congress (APC). The duo are alleging substantial non-compliance with the Electoral Act 2022 in addition to violence and rigging which they claimed marred the conduct and outcome of the election. They had in separate press statements after the election vowed to challenge the outcome of the results in court. On Tuesday, they approached the Tribunal for permission to inspect the materials used by INEC in the conduct of the election. Odoh’s lawyer, Ubah Chukwu prayed the court to grant the Exparte application brought before it pursuant to Section 146 (1) of the Electoral Act 2022, Paragraph 4 of the first Schedule of the Electoral Act of 2022 and under the inherent jurisdiction of the Court as referenced by Section 6 (6) A & B of the 1999 Constitution. In the other application, Odii’s lawyer, Adams Opoke holding a brief for Chris Uche (SAN) also prayed the appellate court to grant the reliefs sought in the motion ex parte in the interest of justice.‒‒:‒‒/‒‒:‒‒ He stated that the motion was brought pursuant to Section 86 (1) of the Constitution of the Federal Republic of Nigeria 1999 as amended Section 146 of the Electoral Act 2022 and paragraphs 47 of the first Schedule of the Electoral Act 2022 under the inherent jurisdiction of the Court. POLL Opoke also informed the Court that they had deposed an affidavit and are relying on all the averments therein in urging the court to grant the application. After listening to the applicants, the presiding judge, Lekan Ogunmoye subsequently granted the request of the two applicants.